ar Lankaran\n* [[Azerbaijan Supercup]] (1): [[2013 Azerbaijan Supercup|2013]]\n\n===International===\n;[[Azerbaijan national under-23 football team|Azerbaijan U23]]\n* [[Islamic Solidarity Games]]: (1) [[2017 Islamic Solidarity Games|2017]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Soccerway|agabala--ramazanov/201979}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramazanov, Aghabala}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baku]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan international footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Neft\u00e7i PFK players]]\n[[Category:Khazar Lankaran FK players]]\n[[Category:Sumgayit FK players]]\n[[Category:Ke\u015fla FK players]]\n[[Category:Qaraba\u011f FK players]]\n[[Category:Sabail FK players]]\n[[Category:Zira FK players]]\n\n{{Azerbaijan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| fullname            = Aghabala Ramazanov\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1993|1|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Azerbaijan]]\n| height              = {{Height|m=1.69}}\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub         = [[Zira FK|Zira]]\n| clubnumber          = 10\n| youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20132011 | youthclubs1 = [[Neftchi PFK|Neftchi Baku]]\n| years1              = 2011\u20132012  | clubs1   = [[Neftchi PFK|Neftchi Baku]]           | caps1 = 1   | goals1 = 0\n| years2              = 2012\u20132015  | clubs2   = [[Khazar Lankaran FK|Khazar Lankaran]] | caps2 = 54  | goals2 = 4\n| years3              = 2015\u20132016  | clubs3   = [[Sumgayit FK|Sumgayit]]               | caps3 = 33  | goals3 = 5\n| years4              = 2016\u20132017  | clubs4   = [[Inter Baku PIK|Inter Baku]]          | caps4 = 13  | goals4 = 4\n| years5              = 2017\u20132018  | clubs5   = [[Qaraba\u011f FK|Qaraba\u011f]]                 | caps5 = 18  | goals5 = 0\n| years6              = 2018\u20132019  | clubs6   = [[Sabail FK|Sabail]]                   | caps6 = 33  | goals6 = 10\n| years7              = 2020\u2013      | clubs7   = [[Zira FK|Zira]]                       | caps7 = 4   | goals7 = 3\n| nationalyears1  = 2013\u20132014 | nationalteam1 = [[Azerbaijan national under-21 football team|Azerbaijan U21]] | nationalcaps1 =  8 | nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2  = 2017      | nationalteam2 = [[Azerbaijan national under-23 football team|Azerbaijan U23]] | nationalcaps2 =  5 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3  = 2014\u2013     | nationalteam3 = [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]]              | nationalcaps3 = 18 | nationalgoals3 = 1\n| club-update         = 9 March 2020\n| nationalteam-update = 20 November 2019 \n}}\n\n'''Aghabala Ramazanov''' (born 20 January 1993) is an Azerbaijani professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Azerbaijan Premier League]] club [[Zira FK]]. He is the brother of [[Zaur Ramazanov]].\n\n==Career==\n===Club===\nIn June 2015, Ramazanov moved from [[Khazar Lankaran FK]] to [[Sumgayit FK]].<ref name=\"Ramazanov signs for Sumgayit\">{{cite web|title=\"Sumqay\u0131t\" FK A\u011fabala Ramazanovu hey\u0259tin\u0259 qat\u0131b|url=http://sumqayitpfc.az/?s=xeber&id=2424|website=sumqayitpfc.az|publisher=[[Sumgayit FK]]|accessdate=3 June 2015|language=Azerbaijani|date=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2018, Qaraba\u011f announced that Ramazanov had been released by the club following expiration of his contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Qaraba\u011f FK-dan bildiri\u015f|url=http://www.qarabagh.com/index.php?name=newsread&type=3&news_id=11244&lang=1|website=qarabagh.com/|publisher=Qaraba\u011f FK|accessdate=24 May 2018|language=Azerbaijani|date=24 May 2018}}</ref> On 26 May 2018, [[Sabail FK]] announced the signing of Ramazanov.<ref name=\"Sabail Sign Agabala Ramazanov\">{{cite web|title=Sabail Sign Agabala Ramazanov|url=https://www.facebook.com/SabailFC/photos/a.1784583645123228.1073741837.1732087423706184/2078497972398459/?type=3|website=facebook.com|publisher=Sabail Facebook|accessdate=27 May 2018|language=Azerbaijani|date=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2018, Ramazanov signed 1.5 years contract with [[Zira FK]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Komandam\u0131z A\u011fabala Ramazanovla m\u00fcqavil\u0259 ba\u011flay\u0131b|url=http://fczire.az/?options=news-view&id=449|website=fczire.az|publisher=FK Zira|accessdate=25 December 2019|language=Azerbaijani}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAghabala is the younger brother of retired [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]] international footballer [[Zaur Ramazanov|Zaur]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0420\u0430\u043c\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0448\u0438\u043b \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u0428\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0444 |url=http://www.azerifootball.com/ru/13/news/44495.html |website=azerifootball.com/ |publisher=Azeri Football |accessdate=16 December 2019 |language=Russian |date=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 21 May 2018}}<ref>{{cite web|title=A.Ramazanov|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/agabala--ramazanov/201979/|website=uk.soccerway.com/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|valign=\"center\"|[[Neftchi PFK|Neftchi Baku]]\n|[[2011\u201312 Neftchi Baku PFC season|2011\u201312]]\n|[[Azerbaijan Premier League]]\n|1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||1||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" valign=\"center\"|[[Khazar Lankaran FK|Khazar Lankaran]]\n|[[2012\u201313 FK Khazar Lankaran season|2012\u201313]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" valign=\"center\"|[[Azerbaijan Premier League]]\n|19||1||5||4||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||24||5\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 FK Khazar Lankaran season|2013\u201314]]\n|21||1||0||0||0||0||1||0||22||1\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 FK Khazar Lankaran season|2014\u201315]]\n|20||5||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||22||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!60!!7!!7!!4!!0!!0!!1!!0!!68!!11\n|-\n|valign=\"center\"|[[Sumgayit FK|Sumgayit]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Sumgayit FK season|2015\u201316]]\n|[[Azerbaijan Premier League]]\n|33||5||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||34||5\n|-\n|valign=\"center\"|[[Inter Baku PIK|Inter Baku]]\n|[[2016\u201317 FC Inter Baku season|2016\u201317]]\n|[[Azerbaijan Premier League]]\n|13||4||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||16||5\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" valign=\"center\"|[[Qaraba\u011f FK|Qaraba\u011f]]\n|[[2016\u201317 FK Qaraba\u011f season|2016\u201317]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"center\"|[[Azerbaijan Premier League]]\n|12||0||3||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||15||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 FK Qaraba\u011f season|2017\u201318]]\n|6||0||0||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||10||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!18!!0!!3!!0!!4!!0!!\u2013!!\u2013!!25!!0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!125!!16!!14!!5!!4!!0!!1!!0!!144!!21\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|[[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2014||1||0\n|-\n|2015||1||1\n|-\n|2016||8||0\n|-\n|2017||2||0\n|-\n|2018||0||0\n|-\n|2019||6||0\n|-\n!Total||18||1\n|}\n''Statistics accurate as of match played 16 November 2019''<ref name=\"NFT Stats\">{{cite web |url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/57471.html |title=A\u011fabala Ramazanov |website=National-Football-Teams.com |access-date=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== International goals ===\n{{updated|17 November 2015}}<ref name=\"NFT Stats\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition !! Ref\n|-\n| 1. || 17 November 2015 || [[Baku Olympic Stadium (BOS)|Baku Olympic Stadium]], [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]] || {{fb|MDA}} || <center>'''2'''\u20131</center> || <center>2\u20131</center> || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]] || <ref>{{cite web|title=Azerbaijan 2-1 Moldova|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/11/17/world/friendlies/azerbaijan/moldova/2141173/|website=uk.soccerway.com/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=20 November 2015|date=17 November 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Honours ==\n;Neftchi Baku\n* [[Azerbaijan Premier League]] (1): [[2011\u201312 Azerbaijan Premier League|2011\u20132012]]\n\n;Qarabag\n* [[Azerbaijan Premier League]] (1): [[2016\u201317 Azerbaijan Premier League|2016\u201317]]\n\n;Khazar Lankaran\n* [[Azerbaijan Supercup]] (1): [[2013 Azerbaijan Supercup|2013]]\n\n===International===\n;[[Azerbaijan national under-23 football team|Azerbaijan U23]]\n* [[Islamic Solidarity Games]]: (1) [[2017 Islamic Solidarity Games|2017]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Soccerway|agabala--ramazanov/201979}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramazanov, Aghabala}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baku]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan international footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Neft\u00e7i PFK players]]\n[[Category:Khazar Lankaran FK players]]\n[[Category:Sumgayit FK players]]\n[[Category:Ke\u015fla FK players]]\n[[Category:Qaraba\u011f FK players]]\n[[Category:Sabail FK players]]\n[[Category:Zira FK players]]\n\n{{Azerbaijan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Azerbaijani footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Azerbaijani footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aghabala_Ramazanov"}
{"title_page": "Limulus amebocyte lysate", "text_new": "{{short description|Chemical used for the detection and quantification of bacterial endotoxins}}\n'''Limulus amebocyte lysate''' ('''LAL''') is an aqueous extract of blood cells ([[amoebocyte]]s) from the [[Atlantic horseshoe crab]], ''Limulus polyphemus''. LAL reacts with bacterial [[lipopolysaccharide|endotoxin lipopolysaccharide]] (LPS), which is a [[cell membrane|membrane]] component of [[gram-negative bacteria]]. This reaction is the basis of the '''LAL test''', which is widely used for the detection and quantification of bacterial endotoxins.\n\nIn Asia, a similar '''Tachypleus amebocyte lysate''' ('''TAL''') test based on the local horseshoe crabs ''[[Tachypleus gigas]]'' or ''[[Tachypleus tridentatus]]'' is occasionally used instead.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sheng J, Zhou J, Peng Y, Zhu Z, Chen L |title=Tachypleus Amebocyte Lysate Test Using in Transfusion Reaction |url=http://wprim.whocc.org.cn/admin/article/articleDetail?WPRIMID=594503&articleId=594503 |journal=Chinese Journal of Nosocomiology |language=Chinese |date=1 January 2006}}</ref> The '''recombinant factor C''' (rFC) assay is a [[#recombinant factor C|replacement]] of LAL/TAL based on a similar reaction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Endotoxin Testing Manufacturers and Conservation |url=https://www.horseshoecrab.org/med/manufacturers.html |website=www.horseshoecrab.org |access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Fred Bang]] reported in 1956 that gram-negative bacteria, even if killed, will cause the blood of the horseshoe crab to turn into a semi-solid mass. It was later recognized that the animal's blood cells, mobile cells called [[amoebocyte]]s, contain granules with a [[clotting factor]] known as [[coagulogen]]; this is released outside the cell when bacterial endotoxin is encountered. The resulting [[coagulation]] (gelling) is thought to contain bacterial infections in the animal's semi-closed [[circulatory system]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greer |first1=Spencer | name-list-format = vanc | work = JH Bloomberg School of Public Health |title=Frederik Bang |url=https://www.jhsph.edu/about/history/heroes-of-public-health/frederik-bang.html | publisher =Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health |language=en}}</ref> Modern analysis of the lysate has led to understanding of this system of cascade, with multiple enzymes working in sequence to produce the gel. The entry point of endotoxin-induced clotting is Limulus clotting factor C.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Iwanaga S | title = Biochemical principle of Limulus test for detecting bacterial endotoxins | journal = Proceedings of the Japan Academy. Series B, Physical and Biological Sciences | volume = 83 | issue = 4 | pages = 110\u20139 | date = May 2007 | pmid = 24019589 | pmc = 3756735 | doi = 10.2183/pjab.83.110 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1977 the [[Food and Drug Administration (United States)|U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) approved LAL for testing drugs, products and devices that come in contact with the blood. Prior to that date, a much slower and more expensive [[Depyrogenation#Pyrogen detection|test on rabbits]] had been used for this purpose.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/05/blood-in-the-water/559229/|title=The Last Days of the Blue-Blood Harvest|last=Zhang|first=Sarah | name-list-format = vanc |date=2018-05-09|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHorseshoe crabs are collected and blood is removed from the horseshoe crab's pericardium; the crabs are then returned to the water.  LAL manufacturers have measured mortality rates of 3% in bled crabs; however, recent studies indicate that this number may be closer to 15%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/nature/episodes/crash-a-tale-of-two-species/the-benefits-of-blue-blood/595/|title=Crash: A Tale of Two Species - The Benefits of Blue Blood|date=10 June 2008|publisher=PBS}}</ref> or even 30%.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Leschen AS, Correia SJ | title = Mortality in female horseshoe crabs (Limulus polyphemus) from biomedical bleeding and handling: implications for fisheries management. | journal = Marine and Freshwater Behaviour and Physiology | date = March 2010 | volume = 43 | issue = 2 | pages = 135\u201347 | url = http://www.mass.gov/dfwele/dmf/publications/mortality_in_female_horseshoe_crabs_abstract.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100614123202/http://www.mass.gov/dfwele/dmf/publications/mortality_in_female_horseshoe_crabs_abstract.pdf  | archive-date=2010-06-14 }}</ref> The blood cells are separated from the serum using [[centrifugation]] and are then placed in distilled water, which causes them to swell and burst (\"lyse\"). This releases the chemicals from the inside of the cell (the \"lysate\"), which is then purified and [[freeze drying|freeze-dried]]. To test a sample for endotoxins, it is mixed with lysate and water; endotoxins are present if coagulation occurs.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mbl.edu/marine_org/images/animals/Limulus/blood/bang.html | title = The History of Limulus and Endotoxin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081028131234/http://www.mbl.edu/marine_org/images/animals/Limulus/blood/bang.html | archive-date=2008-10-28 | publisher = [[Marine Biological Laboratory]] }}</ref>\n\n==The LAL test==\nThere are three basic methodologies: gel-clot, turbidimetric, and chromogenic. The primary application for LAL is the testing of [[Route of administration#Parenteral by injection or infusion|parenteral]] pharmaceuticals and medical devices that contact [[blood]] or [[cerebrospinal fluid]]. In the United States, the FDA has published a guideline for validation of the [https://www.criver.com/products-services/qc-microbial-solutions/endotoxin-testing/lal-reagents-accessories LAL test] as an endotoxin test for such products.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guidance for Industry: Pyrogen and Endotoxins Testing: Questions and Answers|url=https://www.fda.gov/drugs/guidancecomplianceregulatoryinformation/guidances/ucm314718.htm|publisher=U.S. Food and Drug Administration | access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe LAL [[Biochemical cascade|cascade]] is also triggered by (1,3)-\u03b2-D-[[glucan]], via a different Factor G. Both bacterial endotoxins and (1,3)-\u03b2-D-glucan are considered [[pathogen-associated molecular pattern]]s, or PAMPs, substances which elicit inflammatory responses in [[mammal]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sandle T | title = Pharmaceutical product impurities: considering beta glucans. | journal = American Pharmaceutical Review | date = August 2013 | volume = 16 | issue = 5 Supplement S1 | pages = 16\u201319 }}</ref>\n\n===Overcoming inhibition and enhancement===\nOne of the most time-consuming aspects of endotoxin testing using LAL is pretreating samples to overcome assay inhibition that may interfere with the LAL test such that the recovery of endotoxin is affected. If the product being tested causes the endotoxin recovery to be less than expected, the product is inhibitory to the LAL test. Products which cause higher than expected values are enhancing. Overcoming the inhibition and enhancement properties of a product is required by the FDA as part of the validation of the LAL test for use in the final release testing of injectables and medical devices. Proper endotoxin recovery must be proven before LAL can be used to release product.<ref>{{cite book | veditors = Williams KL |title=Endotoxins pyrogens, LAL testing and depyrogenation |date=2007 |publisher=Informa Healthcare |location=New York |isbn=1420020595 |page = 342 | edition=3rd |url= https://archive.org/details/endotoxins00kevi |url-access=registration|quote=Proper endotoxin recovery must be proven before LAL can be used to release product.|access-date=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Alternatives ==\n\n=== Recombinant factor C ===\n{{see also|Atlantic horseshoe crab#Conservation and management}}\n\nThe LAL test makes up a great source of animal product dependence in the biomed industry, and with reports of the higher-than anticipated mortality rate, it was considered more ethical to try to move away from the test. Since 2003, a synthetic substitute for the LAL test has been commercially available. Named the [[Recombinant technology|recombinant]] factor C (rFC) assay, it is based on the same [[Limulus clotting factor C]] protein, produced by genetically modified organisms like insect gut cells. (The specific factor C sequence used does not necessarily come from the Atlantic horseshoe crab.)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nInstead of emulating the whole clotting pathway, rFC tests let factor C cleave a fluorogenic molecule, so that the sample lights up when endotoxin activates the factor. Since it does not contain factor G, (1,3)-\u03b2-D-glucan will not cause false-positives. As of 2018, available evidence considers the rFC test no worse than the LAL test.<ref name=\"rfc\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Maloney T, Phelan R, Simmons N | title = Saving the horseshoe crab: A synthetic alternative to horseshoe crab blood for endotoxin detection | journal = PLoS Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 10 | pages = e2006607 | date = October 2018 | pmid = 30312293 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.2006607 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nThe adoption of this test was slow, which began to change in 2012 when the US FDA and the European health ministry acknowledged it as an accepted alternative. Its lack of mention in Pharmacopeias remained an issue, as there was no good standard for running the test in production.<ref name=\"rfc\"/> In 2016, it was added to the [[European Pharmacopoeia]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A patent on rFC also limited adoption until it expired in 2018.<ref name=\"rfc\"/>\n\n=== Monocyte Activation Test ===\nThe [[monocyte activation test]] (MAT) is another proposed method to test for endotoxins based on [[monocyte]]s in [[human blood]]. It measures the release of [[cytokines]] from these due to the presence of [[Pyrogen (fever)|pyrogen]]s, basically mirroring the process by which these toxins cause fever in humans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alternative Endotoxin Testing Methods |url=https://www.horseshoecrab.org/med/alternatives.html |website=www.horseshoecrab.org}}</ref> A protocol for the MAT test, using cultured cells, is described in the European Pharmacopeia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Monocyte Activation Test: From Validation to GMP Lab testing |url=https://www.americanpharmaceuticalreview.com/Featured-Articles/559493-Monocyte-Activation-Test-From-Validation-to-GMP-Lab-testing/ |website=American Pharmaceutical Review |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Limulus clotting enzyme]]\n* [[Lipopolysaccharide]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.horseshoecrab.org/med/med.html horseshoecrab.org]\n*[http://www.acciusa.com/bet/update/index.html LAL Update]\n* [http://www.indradiagnostics.com/LAL.html Endotoxin Detection Product]\n*[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:adwIP8iyqzwJ:www.fda.gov/downloads/BiologicsBloodVaccines/GuidanceComplianceRegulatoryInformation/Guidances/Blood/UCM080966.pdf+lal+test+fda+guidelines&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiJ5E3owIQNkOVaCc2CxtONrpbditfb3BybssA2iJ-_OMRw1X0WFCNqngtuIS43fXo_xwtBOMjsR78fqtMIJvAcPZr0XcSihTsv41YCsG6WV3M94VTkWXSQX17dh0wrP-oeZjiF&sig=AHIEtbSJEm7e-Te6PKkJAc9JPxWdMnIAAw 1987 FDA LAL test guideline ]\n\n[[Category:Chemical tests]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chemical used for the detection and quantification of bacterial endotoxins}}\n'''Limulus amebocyte lysate''' ('''LAL''') is an aqueous extract of blood cells ([[amoebocyte]]s) from the [[Atlantic horseshoe crab]], ''Limulus polyphemus''. LAL reacts with bacterial [[lipopolysaccharide|endotoxin lipopolysaccharide]] (LPS), which is a [[cell membrane|membrane]] component of [[gram-negative bacteria]]. This reaction is the basis of the '''LAL test''', which is widely used for the detection and quantification of bacterial endotoxins.\n\nIn Asia, a similar '''Tachypleus amebocyte lysate''' ('''TAL''') test based on the local horseshoe crabs ''[[Tachypleus gigas]]'' or ''[[Tachypleus tridentatus]]'' is occasionally used instead.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sheng J, Zhou J, Peng Y, Zhu Z, Chen L |title=Tachypleus Amebocyte Lysate Test Using in Transfusion Reaction |url=http://wprim.whocc.org.cn/admin/article/articleDetail?WPRIMID=594503&articleId=594503 |journal=Chinese Journal of Nosocomiology |language=Chinese |date=1 January 2006}}</ref> The '''recombinant factor C''' (rFC) assay is a [[#recombinant factor C|replacement]] of LAL/TAL based on a similar reaction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Endotoxin Testing Manufacturers and Conservation |url=https://www.horseshoecrab.org/med/manufacturers.html |website=www.horseshoecrab.org |access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Fred Bang]] reported in 1956 that gram-negative bacteria, even if killed, will cause the blood of the horseshoe crab to turn into a semi-solid mass. It was later recognized that the animal's blood cells, mobile cells called [[amoebocyte]]s, contain granules with a [[clotting factor]] known as [[coagulogen]]; this is released outside the cell when bacterial endotoxin is encountered. The resulting [[coagulation]] (gelling) is thought to contain bacterial infections in the animal's semi-closed [[circulatory system]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greer |first1=Spencer | name-list-format = vanc | work = JH Bloomberg School of Public Health |title=Frederik Bang |url=https://www.jhsph.edu/about/history/heroes-of-public-health/frederik-bang.html | publisher =Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health |language=en}}</ref> Modern analysis of the lysate has led to understanding of this system of cascade, with multiple enzymes working in sequence to produce the gel. The entry point of endotoxin-induced clotting is Limulus clotting factor C.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Iwanaga S | title = Biochemical principle of Limulus test for detecting bacterial endotoxins | journal = Proceedings of the Japan Academy. Series B, Physical and Biological Sciences | volume = 83 | issue = 4 | pages = 110\u20139 | date = May 2007 | pmid = 24019589 | pmc = 3756735 | doi = 10.2183/pjab.83.110 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1977 the [[Food and Drug Administration (United States)|U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) approved LAL for testing drugs, products and devices that come in contact with the blood. Prior to that date, a much slower and more expensive [[Depyrogenation#Pyrogen detection|test on rabbits]] had been used for this purpose.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/05/blood-in-the-water/559229/|title=The Last Days of the Blue-Blood Harvest|last=Zhang|first=Sarah | name-list-format = vanc |date=2018-05-09|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHorseshoe crabs are collected and blood is removed from the horseshoe crab's pericardium; the crabs are then returned to the water.  LAL manufacturers have measured mortality rates of 3% in bled crabs; however, recent studies indicate that this number may be closer to 15%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/nature/episodes/crash-a-tale-of-two-species/the-benefits-of-blue-blood/595/|title=Crash: A Tale of Two Species - The Benefits of Blue Blood|date=10 June 2008|publisher=PBS}}</ref> or even 30%.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Leschen AS, Correia SJ | title = Mortality in female horseshoe crabs (Limulus polyphemus) from biomedical bleeding and handling: implications for fisheries management. | journal = Marine and Freshwater Behaviour and Physiology | date = March 2010 | volume = 43 | issue = 2 | pages = 135\u201347 | url = http://www.mass.gov/dfwele/dmf/publications/mortality_in_female_horseshoe_crabs_abstract.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100614123202/http://www.mass.gov/dfwele/dmf/publications/mortality_in_female_horseshoe_crabs_abstract.pdf  | archive-date=2010-06-14 }}</ref> The blood cells are separated from the serum using [[centrifugation]] and are then placed in distilled water, which causes them to swell and burst (\"lyse\"). This releases the chemicals from the inside of the cell (the \"lysate\"), which is then purified and [[freeze drying|freeze-dried]]. To test a sample for endotoxins, it is mixed with lysate and water; endotoxins are present if coagulation occurs.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mbl.edu/marine_org/images/animals/Limulus/blood/bang.html | title = The History of Limulus and Endotoxin | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081028131234/http://www.mbl.edu/marine_org/images/animals/Limulus/blood/bang.html | archive-date=2008-10-28 | publisher = [[Marine Biological Laboratory]] }}</ref>\n\n==The LAL test==\nThere are three basic methodologies: gel-clot, turbidimetric, and chromogenic. The primary application for LAL is the testing of [[Route of administration#Parenteral by injection or infusion|parenteral]] pharmaceuticals and medical devices that contact [[blood]] or [[cerebrospinal fluid]]. In the United States, the FDA has published a guideline for validation of the LAL test as an endotoxin test for such products.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guidance for Industry: Pyrogen and Endotoxins Testing: Questions and Answers|url=https://www.fda.gov/drugs/guidancecomplianceregulatoryinformation/guidances/ucm314718.htm|publisher=U.S. Food and Drug Administration | access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe LAL [[Biochemical cascade|cascade]] is also triggered by (1,3)-\u03b2-D-[[glucan]], via a different Factor G. Both bacterial endotoxins and (1,3)-\u03b2-D-glucan are considered [[pathogen-associated molecular pattern]]s, or PAMPs, substances which elicit inflammatory responses in [[mammal]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sandle T | title = Pharmaceutical product impurities: considering beta glucans. | journal = American Pharmaceutical Review | date = August 2013 | volume = 16 | issue = 5 Supplement S1 | pages = 16\u201319 }}</ref>\n\n===Overcoming inhibition and enhancement===\nOne of the most time-consuming aspects of endotoxin testing using LAL is pretreating samples to overcome assay inhibition that may interfere with the LAL test such that the recovery of endotoxin is affected. If the product being tested causes the endotoxin recovery to be less than expected, the product is inhibitory to the LAL test. Products which cause higher than expected values are enhancing. Overcoming the inhibition and enhancement properties of a product is required by the FDA as part of the validation of the LAL test for use in the final release testing of injectables and medical devices. Proper endotoxin recovery must be proven before LAL can be used to release product.<ref>{{cite book | veditors = Williams KL |title=Endotoxins pyrogens, LAL testing and depyrogenation |date=2007 |publisher=Informa Healthcare |location=New York |isbn=1420020595 |page = 342 | edition=3rd |url= https://archive.org/details/endotoxins00kevi |url-access=registration|quote=Proper endotoxin recovery must be proven before LAL can be used to release product.|access-date=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Alternatives ==\n\n=== Recombinant factor C ===\n{{see also|Atlantic horseshoe crab#Conservation and management}}\n\nThe LAL test makes up a great source of animal product dependence in the biomed industry, and with reports of the higher-than anticipated mortality rate, it was considered more ethical to try to move away from the test. Since 2003, a synthetic substitute for the LAL test has been commercially available. Named the [[Recombinant technology|recombinant]] factor C (rFC) assay, it is based on the same [[Limulus clotting factor C]] protein, produced by genetically modified organisms like insect gut cells. (The specific factor C sequence used does not necessarily come from the Atlantic horseshoe crab.)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nInstead of emulating the whole clotting pathway, rFC tests let factor C cleave a fluorogenic molecule, so that the sample lights up when endotoxin activates the factor. Since it does not contain factor G, (1,3)-\u03b2-D-glucan will not cause false-positives. As of 2018, available evidence considers the rFC test no worse than the LAL test.<ref name=\"rfc\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Maloney T, Phelan R, Simmons N | title = Saving the horseshoe crab: A synthetic alternative to horseshoe crab blood for endotoxin detection | journal = PLoS Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 10 | pages = e2006607 | date = October 2018 | pmid = 30312293 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.2006607 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nThe adoption of this test was slow, which began to change in 2012 when the US FDA and the European health ministry acknowledged it as an accepted alternative. Its lack of mention in Pharmacopeias remained an issue, as there was no good standard for running the test in production.<ref name=\"rfc\"/> In 2016, it was added to the [[European Pharmacopoeia]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A patent on rFC also limited adoption until it expired in 2018.<ref name=\"rfc\"/>\n\n=== Monocyte Activation Test ===\nThe [[monocyte activation test]] (MAT) is another proposed method to test for endotoxins based on [[monocyte]]s in [[human blood]]. It measures the release of [[cytokines]] from these due to the presence of [[Pyrogen (fever)|pyrogen]]s, basically mirroring the process by which these toxins cause fever in humans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alternative Endotoxin Testing Methods |url=https://www.horseshoecrab.org/med/alternatives.html |website=www.horseshoecrab.org}}</ref> A protocol for the MAT test, using cultured cells, is described in the European Pharmacopeia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Monocyte Activation Test: From Validation to GMP Lab testing |url=https://www.americanpharmaceuticalreview.com/Featured-Articles/559493-Monocyte-Activation-Test-From-Validation-to-GMP-Lab-testing/ |website=American Pharmaceutical Review |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Limulus clotting enzyme]]\n* [[Lipopolysaccharide]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.horseshoecrab.org/med/med.html horseshoecrab.org]\n*[http://www.acciusa.com/bet/update/index.html LAL Update]\n* [http://www.indradiagnostics.com/LAL.html Endotoxin Detection Product]\n*[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:adwIP8iyqzwJ:www.fda.gov/downloads/BiologicsBloodVaccines/GuidanceComplianceRegulatoryInformation/Guidances/Blood/UCM080966.pdf+lal+test+fda+guidelines&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiJ5E3owIQNkOVaCc2CxtONrpbditfb3BybssA2iJ-_OMRw1X0WFCNqngtuIS43fXo_xwtBOMjsR78fqtMIJvAcPZr0XcSihTsv41YCsG6WV3M94VTkWXSQX17dh0wrP-oeZjiF&sig=AHIEtbSJEm7e-Te6PKkJAc9JPxWdMnIAAw 1987 FDA LAL test guideline ]\n\n[[Category:Chemical tests]]\n", "name_user": "Smiller.charlesriver", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link to resource", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limulus_amebocyte_lysate"}
{"title_page": "Hamilton (musical)", "text_new": "{{about|the Broadway musical|the 2015 Broadway cast recording|Hamilton (album)|the 2016 album inspired by the show|The Hamilton Mixtape|the upcoming film|Hamilton (2021 film)}}\n{{short description|2015 musical by Lin-Manuel Miranda about Alexander Hamilton}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{use American English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical\n| name          = Hamilton\n| subtitle      = An American Musical\n| image         = Hamilton-poster.jpg\n| caption       = \n| alt           = \n| music         = [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]]\n| lyrics        = Lin-Manuel Miranda\n| book          = Lin-Manuel Miranda<!-- Note, in this context \"book\" refers to the spoken dialogue of a stage musical, i.s. [[Book (musical theatre)]], not the Chernow text that inspired Miranda -->\n| basis         = ''[[Alexander Hamilton (book)|Alexander Hamilton]]''<br>by [[Ron Chernow]]\n| premiere_date = January 20, 2015\n| premiere_location = [[The Public Theater]], [[New York City]]\n| productions   = <!-- Per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Musical Theatre/Article Structure]], future productions are not listed until they begin previews -->2013 [[Vassar College]]<br>2015 [[Off-Broadway]]<br>2015 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]<br>2016 [[Theater in Chicago|Chicago]]<br> 2017 first North America tour<br> 2017 [[West End theatre|West End]]<br> 2018 second North America tour <br> 2019 third  North America tour\n<!-- Please do not include production-specific (acting, directing, etc.) awards -->\n| awards         = {{hidden|List of awards|{{\u2022}}[[Tony Award for Best Musical]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Tony Award for Best Original Score]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in Music]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Musical]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Book of a Musical]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Lyrics]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[New York Drama Critics' Circle Award]] for Best Musical<br>{{\u2022}}[[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Outstanding New Off-Broadway Musical<br>{{\u2022}}[[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Outstanding New Score<br>{{\u2022}}[[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Outstanding Book of a Musical<br>{{\u2022}}[[Lucille Lortel Award]] for Outstanding Musical<br>{{\u2022}}[[Obie Award]] for Best New American Theatre Work<br>{{\u2022}}[[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]]<br>{{\u2022}}[[Drama League Award]] for Outstanding Production of a Broadway or Off-Broadway Musical}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Lin-Manuel Miranda, Phillipa Soo, Leslie Odom, Jr., and Christopher Jackson, White House, March 2016.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|Cast members perform musical selections at the [[White House]], 2016. L-R: [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], [[Phillipa Soo]], [[Leslie Odom Jr.]], and [[Christopher Jackson (actor)|Christopher Jackson]] ]]\n\n'''''Hamilton''''' is a musical with music, lyrics, and book by [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]] that tells the story of American [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Founding Father]] [[Alexander Hamilton]].  Inspired by the 2004 biography ''[[Alexander Hamilton (book)|Alexander Hamilton]]'' by historian [[Ron Chernow]], the show's music draws heavily from [[hip hop]], as well as [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[pop music|pop]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[show tune|traditional-style show tunes]]; the show also incorporates color-conscious casting of [[Person of color|non-white]] actors as the Founding Fathers and other historical figures.<ref name=\"Cote\" /><ref name=\"mead\" /><ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite journal|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=March 2016|title=''Hamilton'': Casting After Colorblindness|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/03/hamilton-casting/476247/|url-status=live|journal=[[The Atlantic]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607115823/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/03/hamilton-casting/476247/|archivedate=June 7, 2017|quote=''Hamilton'' is not, by the common definition, colorblind. It does not merely allow for some of the Founding Fathers to be played by people of color. It insists that all of them be.}}</ref> Through this use of modern storytelling methods, ''Hamilton'' has been described as being about \"America then, as told by America now.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dpacnc.com/events/detail/hamilton-1|title=Hamilton|publisher=DPAC Official Site|website=www.dpacnc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\nFrom its first opening, ''Hamilton'' received critical acclaim.<ref name=\"Economist2015\">{{cite news |title=Patriotism on Broadway |work=The Economist |date=December 19, 2015 |accessdate=December 12, 2015 |url=https://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21684118-why-everyone-wants-see-hamilton-patriotism-broadway |quote=Near-universal critical acclaim... |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151217042153/http://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21684118-why-everyone-wants-see-hamilton-patriotism-broadway |archivedate=December 17, 2015 }}</ref> The show premiered at the [[The Public Theater|Public Theater]], [[Off-Broadway]] on February 17, 2015, where its engagement was sold out;<ref name=\"Revolutionary\" /> it won eight Drama Desk Awards, including [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Musical|Outstanding Musical]]. It then transferred to the [[Richard Rodgers Theatre]] on Broadway, opening on August 6, 2015, where it received uniformly positive reviews and strikingly high box office sales.<ref name=\"paulson2015\" /> At the [[2016 Tony Awards]], ''Hamilton'' received a record-setting 16 nominations, eventually winning 11 awards, including [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]]. It received the 2016 [[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]].\n\nThe [[Theater in Chicago|Chicago]] production of ''Hamilton'' began preview performances at the [[CIBC Theatre]] in September 2016 and officially opened the following month.<ref name=\"chicago\">{{cite web |last=Viagas |first=Robert |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/breaking-leads-announced-for-chicago-hamilton |title=Leads Announced for Chicago 'Hamilton' |website=[[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]]|date=July 13, 2016}}</ref> The [[West End theatre|West End]] production of ''Hamilton'' opened at the [[Victoria Palace Theatre]] in [[London]] in December 2017, winning seven [[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Awards]] in 2018, including [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical|Best New Musical]].<ref name=\"WestEnd2017\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/theatre/what-to-see/west-end-hamilton-is-coming---how-to-make-sure-you-tickets/ |title=Hamilton London tickets: tout-beating ticket strategy, prices and how to buy them in today's general sale |last=Vincent |first=Alice |date=January 30, 2017 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218081136/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/theatre/what-to-see/west-end-hamilton-is-coming---how-to-make-sure-you-tickets/ |archivedate=February 18, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first U.S. national tour of the show began performances in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hamiltonbroadway.com/tour.php |title=Hamilton \u2013 Official Broadway Site \u2013 Get Tickets |website=Hamilton |date=August 25, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825235818/http://www.hamiltonbroadway.com/tour.php |archivedate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> A second U.S. tour opened in February 2018.<ref name=\"Desk\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Breaking-News-HAMILTON-to-Kick-Off-Second-National-Tour-in-the-Pacific-Northwest-20170313 |title=Breaking News: HAMILTON to Kick Off Second National Tour in the Pacific Northwest |author=BWW News Desk |date=March 13, 2017 |work=BroadwayWorld.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313235752/http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Breaking-News-HAMILTON-to-Kick-Off-Second-National-Tour-in-the-Pacific-Northwest-20170313 |archivedate=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Hamilton''{{'}}s third U.S. tour began January 11, 2019, with a three-week engagement  in [[Puerto Rico]] featuring Miranda in the lead role.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/everything-we-know-so-far-about-lin-manuel-mirandas-hamilton-in-puerto-rico|title=Everything We Know So Far About Lin-Manuel Miranda's Hamilton in Puerto Rico|first=Cleo|last=Aukland|date=November 12, 2018|magazine=[[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/26/theater/hamilton-puerto-rico-lin-manuel-miranda.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Farts&action=click&contentCollection=arts&region=rank&module=package&version=highlights&contentPlacement=1&pgtype=sectionfront |title=Lin-Manuel Miranda's Passion for Puerto Rico |first=Michael |last=Paulson |date=December 26, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n== Synopsis ==\n{{Long plot|date=July 2019}}\nThe musical details Hamilton's life in two acts, along with how various historical characters influenced his life such as [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette]], [[Aaron Burr]], [[John Laurens]], [[Hercules Mulligan]], [[Elizabeth Schuyler Hamilton]], [[Angelica Schuyler]], [[Peggy Schuyler]], [[Philip Hamilton]], and former presidents [[George Washington]], [[James Madison]], and [[Thomas Jefferson]].\n\n=== Act I ===\nThe orphan [[Alexander Hamilton]] leaves his home on the [[island of Nevis]] (\"[[Alexander Hamilton (song)|Alexander Hamilton]]\"). After arriving in New York in 1776, Hamilton meets [[Aaron Burr]], [[John Laurens]], [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette|Marquis de Lafayette]], and [[Hercules Mulligan]] (\"[[Aaron Burr, Sir]]\"), and impresses them with his rhetorical skills (\"[[My Shot]]\"). They affirm their revolutionary goals to each other (\"[[The Story of Tonight]]\"). Meanwhile, wealthy sisters [[Angelica Schuyler Church|Angelica]], [[Elizabeth Schuyler Hamilton|Eliza]], and [[Peggy Schuyler]] go into town seeking out potential suitors (\"[[The Schuyler Sisters]]\"). [[Samuel Seabury]] warns everyone about the dangers of Congress, but Hamilton disagrees and tries to counter Seabury (\"[[Farmer Refuted]]\"). [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George]] then insists on his authority (\"[[You'll Be Back]]\"). During the [[New York and New Jersey campaign]], Hamilton accepts a position as [[George Washington]]'s [[aide-de-camp]] (\"[[Right Hand Man (Hamilton song)|Right Hand Man]]\"), instead of field command.\n\nAt Philip Schuyler's ball (\"A Winter's Ball\"),  Hamilton meets, falls in love with, and later marries Eliza Schuyler (\"[[Helpless (Hamilton song)|Helpless]]\"), as Angelica suppresses her feelings for the sake of their happiness at the wedding (\"[[Satisfied (Hamilton song)|Satisfied]]\"). After the wedding, Burr congratulates Hamilton on his position as aide-de-camp to Washington; Hamilton admits that he would much rather have Burr's position on the battlefield (\"[[The Story of Tonight (Reprise)]]\"). Burr reflects on Hamilton's swift rise while considering his own career as more cautious (\"[[Wait for It (song)|Wait For It]]\").\n\nAs conditions worsen for the Continental Army, Hamilton aids Laurens in a [[duel]] against [[Charles Lee (general)|Charles Lee]] (\"Stay Alive\"), who insulted Washington. Laurens injures Lee, who in turn yields (\"[[Ten Duel Commandments]]\"). Hamilton is temporarily suspended by Washington (\"Meet Me Inside\") over the duel and is sent home. There, Eliza reveals that she is pregnant with her first child, and asks Hamilton to slow down to take in what has happened in their lives (\"That Would Be Enough\"). After Lafayette convinces France to get involved on the colonists' side (\"Guns and Ships\"), he urges Washington to call Hamilton back to help plan the final [[Siege of Yorktown]]. Washington agrees but explains to Hamilton\u2014who is convinced he should die a martyr and a hero in war\u2014that he should be careful with his actions because whatever he does will be known for ages to come (\"[[History Has Its Eyes on You]]\"). At the [[Siege of Yorktown]], Hamilton meets up with Lafayette to take down the British, revealing that Mulligan was recruited as a spy, helping them figure out how to trap the British and win the war (\"[[Yorktown (The World Turned Upside Down)]]\").\n\nSoon after the victory at Yorktown, King George asks the rebels how they will succeed in governing on their own (\u201c[[You'll Be Back|What Comes Next?]]\u201d). Lafayette returns to France with plans to inspire his people to have [[The French Revolution|their own revolution]]. Hamilton's son [[Philip Hamilton|Philip]] is born, while Burr has a daughter, [[Theodosia Burr Alston|Theodosia]], and the two tell their children how they will do anything to protect them (\"[[Dear Theodosia]]\"). Hamilton receives word that his friend Laurens has been killed in [[Battle of the Combahee River|a seemingly pointless battle]] after the war was won and throws himself into his work (\"[[Tomorrow There'll Be More of Us]]\"). He co-authors ''[[The Federalist Papers]]'' and is selected as [[Secretary of the Treasury (United States)|Secretary of the Treasury]] by newly elected President Washington. Eliza begs Hamilton to stay. Angelica moves to London with her new husband (\"Non-Stop\").\n\n=== Act II ===\n[[Thomas Jefferson]] returns to America from being the [[List of ambassadors of the United States to France|U.S. ambassador to France]] (\"What'd I Miss\"). In 1789, Jefferson and Hamilton debate the latter's financial proposals at a [[Cabinet of the United States|Cabinet]] meeting. Washington pulls Hamilton aside, and tells him to figure out a compromise to win over Congress (\"[[Cabinet Battle]] #1\").\n\nEliza and her family\u2014along with Angelica, back from London\u2014travel upstate during the summer, while Hamilton stays home to work on the compromise (\"Take a Break\"). Hamilton [[Hamilton\u2013Reynolds sex scandal|begins an affair]] with [[Maria Reynolds]], making him vulnerable to her husband's blackmail (\"[[Say No To This]]\"). Hamilton, Jefferson, and [[James Madison]] create the [[Compromise of 1790]] over a private dinner, exchanging Hamilton's financial plan for placing the country's permanent capital on the Potomac River. Burr is envious of Hamilton's sway in the government and wishes he had similar power (\"[[The Room Where It Happens]]\"). Burr switches political parties and defeats Philip Schuyler, making Hamilton now a rival (\"Schuyler Defeated\").\n\nIn another Cabinet meeting, Jefferson and Hamilton argue over whether the United States should assist France in its [[War of the First Coalition|conflict with Britain]]. President Washington ultimately agrees with Hamilton's argument for remaining [[Proclamation of Neutrality|neutral]] (\"[[Cabinet Battle]] #2\"). In the wake of this, Jefferson, Madison, and Burr decide to join forces to find a way to discredit Hamilton in Washington's eyes (\"Washington on Your Side\"). Washington decides to retire from the presidency, and Hamilton assists in writing a [[George Washington's Farewell Address|farewell address]] (\"[[One Last Time (Hamilton)|One Last Time]]\").\n\nA flabbergasted King George receives word that George Washington has stepped down, and will be replaced by [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Paris]] signatory [[John Adams]] (\u201cI Know Him\u201d). John Adams [[1796 United States presidential election|becomes the second President]] and fires Hamilton, who publishes an inflammatory critique of the new president as a response (\"[[The Adams Administration]]\"). In the face of accusations of speculation of government funds by Jefferson, Madison, and Burr\u2014and out of fear that his affair with Maria Reynolds will be used against him in his political career (\"We Know\")\u2014Hamilton chooses to publicize his affair (\"Hurricane\") in the Reynolds Pamphlet (\"[[The Reynolds Pamphlet (song)|The Reynolds Pamphlet]]\"), damaging his relationship with Eliza. Eliza, in a heartbroken retaliation, burns all the letters Hamilton wrote her (\"Burn\"). Philip, instructed by Hamilton, challenges [[George Eacker]] to a duel and is critically injured (\"Blow Us All Away\") and dies (\"Stay Alive (Reprise)\"), causing a reconciliation between Alexander and Eliza (\"[[It's Quiet Uptown]]\").\n\nHamilton's endorsement of Jefferson in [[1800 United States presidential election|the presidential election of 1800]] (\"The Election of 1800\") results in further animosity between Hamilton and Burr, who [[Burr\u2013Hamilton duel|challenges Hamilton to a duel]] via an exchange of letters (\"[[Your Obedient Servant (song)|Your Obedient Servant]]\"). Hamilton writes his last letter in a rush while Eliza tells him to go back to bed (\u201cBest of Wives and Best of Women\u201d). Burr and Hamilton travel to New Jersey for the duel. During the duel, both Burr and Hamilton fire at each other after ten paces, with Hamilton intentionally missing (''[[Deloping|throwing away]]'') his shot. Hamilton dies as a result, with Eliza and Angelica at his side. Burr laments that even though he survived, he is cursed to be remembered as the villain who killed Hamilton (\"[[The World Was Wide Enough]]\"). The musical closes with a reflection on historical memory, showing how Eliza kept Hamilton's legacy alive (\"[[Who Lives, Who Dies, Who Tells Your Story]]\").\n\n== Roles and principal casts ==\n=== Original production casts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Character\n! Vassar workshop<ref name=\"bloom\">{{Cite news |last=Boroff |first=Philip |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-08-02/hip-hop-hero-alexander-hamilton-supertutors-eye-broadway |title=Hip-Hop Hero Alexander Hamilton, Supertutors Eye Broadway |date=August 1, 2013 |journal=Bloomberg Muse |publisher=Bloomberg |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925055855/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-08-02/hip-hop-hero-alexander-hamilton-supertutors-eye-broadway |archivedate=September 25, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n! Off-Broadway<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/hamilton-ends-sold-out-off-broadway-run-tonight-broadway-revolution-is-next-348197 \" 'Hamilton' Ends Sold-Out Off-Broadway Run Tonight \u2013 Broadway Revolution Is Next\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706020407/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/hamilton-ends-sold-out-off-broadway-run-tonight-broadway-revolution-is-next-348197 |date=July 6, 2015 }} playbill.com, May 3, 2015</ref>\n! Broadway<ref name=\"BwayCasting\">{{cite web |last=Hetrick |first=Adam |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-revolution-is-coming-meet-the-full-cast-of-broadways-hamilton-351663 |title=The Revolution Is Coming! Meet the Full Cast of Broadway's ''Hamilton''! |work=Playbill |date=June 18, 2015 |accessdate=July 4, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619053800/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-revolution-is-coming-meet-the-full-cast-of-broadways-hamilton-351663 |archivedate=June 19, 2015}}</ref>\n! Chicago<ref name=\"chicago\" />\n! First U.S. tour<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Breaking-News-Joshua-Henry-Michael-Luwoye-and-Rory-OMalley-Will-Go-Non-Stop-in-HAMILTON-National-Tour-Cast-Announced-20170105 |title=Breaking News: Joshua Henry, Michael Luwoye and Rory O'Malley Will Go 'Non-Stop' in HAMILTON National Tour; Cast Announced! |author=BWW News Desk |date=Jan 5, 2017 |newspaper=BroadwayWorld.com |access-date=January 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106103133/http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Breaking-News-Joshua-Henry-Michael-Luwoye-and-Rory-OMalley-Will-Go-Non-Stop-in-HAMILTON-National-Tour-Cast-Announced-20170105 |archivedate=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n! West End<ref name=\"broadway.com\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/187419/rachelle-ann-go-more-west-end-favorites-tapped-for-hamilton-in-londons-west-end/ |title=Rachelle Ann Go & More West End Favorites Tapped for Hamilton in London's West End |newspaper=Broadway.com |access-date=January 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129045753/http://www.broadway.com/buzz/187419/rachelle-ann-go-more-west-end-favorites-tapped-for-hamilton-in-londons-west-end/ |archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n! Second U.S. tour<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/190635/in-the-room-where-it-happens-joseph-morales-nik-walker-to-headline-the-blockbuster-hamilton-tour/ |title=In the Room Where It Happens! Joseph Morales & Nik Walker to Headline the Blockbuster Hamilton Tour |work=Broadway.com |access-date=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n!Puerto Rico<ref name=\"playbill.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/lin-manuel-miranda-will-star-in-hamilton-in-puerto-rico |title=Lin-Manuel Miranda Will Star in Hamilton in Puerto Rico|website=Playbill|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n!Third U.S. tour<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/new-hamilton-tour-to-star-julius-thomas-iii-and-donald-webber-jr|title=New Hamilton Tour to Star Julius Thomas III and Donald Webber Jr.|first=Ryan|last=McPhee|date=November 12, 2018|website=Playbill}}</ref>\n! Los Angeles <ref>http://www.playbill.com/article/jamael-westman-taylor-iman-jones-rory-omalley-more-will-star-in-los-angeles-run-of-hamilton</ref>\n|-\n! [[Alexander Hamilton]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Miguel Cervantes \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Michael Luwoye]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Jamael Westman\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Joseph Morales]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Lin-Manuel M